00:00:59.119 --> 00:01:07.839
progressed through that. So the first couple of slides are a little bit complex and a little bit

00:01:07.839 --> 00:01:16.639
wordy so I apologize for that please bear with me we'll get on to the data science side of things

00:01:17.199 --> 00:01:22.879
very quickly but I just would like to set the scene of what the smart DCC done why we've had

00:01:22.879 --> 00:01:31.440
to make some of the decisions that we have so let's go on to the first slide. As I said I'm

00:01:31.440 --> 00:01:38.080
head of data science at the data communications company the DCC. It's important to understand

00:01:38.160 --> 00:01:43.199
what the DCC is. We're a licensed and regulated body that was set up

00:01:47.279 --> 00:01:57.760
and established the United Kingdom to roll out smart meters across the country. We were

00:01:57.760 --> 00:02:05.599
set up and licensed by BASE which is a government department so our license was enacted as part of

00:02:05.599 --> 00:02:16.080
parliament and we are regulated by the energy watchdog Ofgem who watch out for everyone. The

00:02:16.080 --> 00:02:25.440
license started in 2013 but we didn't start installing meters until about 2017 and one of

00:02:25.440 --> 00:02:33.440
the most important things to consider as part of our journey is that we are scrutinized with every

00:02:33.440 --> 00:02:38.080
cost we have. We have a price control and everything must be agreed with our stakeholders

00:02:38.800 --> 00:02:45.600
and also our customers. Our stakeholders being the government and the Ofgem and our customers

00:02:45.600 --> 00:02:48.320
being the energy suppliers, the network operators.

00:02:49.279 --> 00:02:58.880
So our network is the network that connects these smart meters across the country to the

00:02:58.880 --> 00:03:06.559
users of the system and at the moment we've got about 13 million meters that are connected

00:03:06.559 --> 00:03:12.880
across the solution. That will rise in the next year or so and we're going to be

00:03:12.960 --> 00:03:19.440
15 million meters that are connected across the solution. That will rise to about 50 million

00:03:19.440 --> 00:03:26.240
meters and about 250 million connected devices that will be on our network. So really we're a

00:03:26.240 --> 00:03:34.399
very large scale IoT solution. Our whole network is rolled out by our service providers so the DCC

00:03:34.399 --> 00:03:43.119
themselves do not provide any infrastructure or any kit really. We manage our service providers

00:03:43.119 --> 00:03:48.720
who do that. At the moment we have about 15 million messages across our network every day so

00:03:48.720 --> 00:03:55.600
it's quite a busy network but on top of that we also have all the inventory data that is there

00:03:55.600 --> 00:04:03.919
to support all of that. At GoLive everything was outsourced as I said including our analytics

00:04:04.399 --> 00:04:11.279
so the DCC did not provide any analytics at that point but we were mandated to have a

00:04:13.279 --> 00:04:21.839
reporting function that was responsible for governing and distributing the reports.

00:04:21.839 --> 00:04:28.079
But they would check the QA check them and as part of this they would have SQL access into it.

00:04:28.079 --> 00:04:31.920
So just a little bit of SQL just enough to go in and check that our reports were right but we did

00:04:31.920 --> 00:04:37.760
not have an analytics function. But now we've grown from a team of 4 to 16. We've taken all

00:04:37.760 --> 00:04:44.320
the analytics in-house now so the DCC provides it all. It's been a journey to get there and I'll

00:04:44.320 --> 00:04:52.880
take you through that step. We've got a complex data set and what feels like a large data set as well

00:04:52.880 --> 00:04:59.040
and it's growing all the time as we get busier and busier and more installs happen. We've also got a

00:04:59.040 --> 00:05:03.760
huge customer base where we've got over 100 customers that we have to satisfy across the

00:05:03.760 --> 00:05:07.679
solution and they all use it in a slightly different way. So that's where we are now.

